definition.value: Antenatal Bartter syndrome is a phenotypic variant of Bartter syndrome (see this term) presenting antenatally with maternal polyhydramnios, pre-term delivery and postnatally with polyuria, and nephrocalcinosis. Hypokalemic alkalosis, increased levels of plasma renin and aldosterone, low blood pressure and vascular resistance to angiotensin II are characteristically associated. Genotypically they comprise Type 1 and Type 2 Bartter syndrome

Classic Bartter syndrome is a type of Bartter syndrome (see this term), characterized by a milder clinical picture than the antenatal/infantile subtype, and presenting with failure to thrive, hypokalemic alkalosis, increased levels of plasma renin and aldosterone, low blood pressure and vascular resistance to angiotensin II.

Distal renal tubular acidosis with anemia

definition.value: Distal renal tubular acidosis (dRTA) with anemia is a very rare form of distal renal tubular acidosis (dRTA; see this term) characterized by a defect in renal acidification and hereditary hemolytic anemia.
Dent disease type 1 is a type of Dent disease (see this term) with predominantly renal manifestations.
Dent disease type 2 is a type of Dent disease in which patients have the manifestations of Dent disease type 1 (see this term) associated with extra-renal features.

label.value: X-linked dominant intellectual disability - epilepsy syndrome

definition.value: Benign essential blepharospasm (BEB) is a cerebral focal and functional dystonia characterized by involuntary excessive blinking that can lead, in severe cases, to functional blindness due to the impossibility of re-opening the eyes at will.
Truncal dystonia is a form of focal dystonia (see this term), characterized by involuntary back arching often associated with pain and severe motor disability.

Focal limb dystonia is a form of focal dystonia (see this term), characterized by dystonic spasms of arm or leg muscles accompanied by repetitive, twisting movements or abnormal positions or postures. Limb dystonia may also be segmental, that is affecting group of muscles of an arm as well as the neck, and is also present in those with hemidystonia or generalized dystonia.

Laryngeal dyskinesia (LD) a form of focal dystonia (see this term) that affects laryngeal motor control and is characterized by involuntary adductor or abductor vocal fold spasms during phonation which result in altered phonatory and respiratory functions.

Cervical dystonia (CD) is the most common type of focal dystonia (see this term) and is characterized by overactive neck muscles with involuntary turning, tilting or twisting of the head which result in torticollis, laterocollis, retrocollis, and anterocollis.

label.value: obsolete_Autosomal dominant focal dystonia, DYT7 type

definition.value: Focal dystonia DYT7 type is characterized by predominantly cervical and laryngeal dystonia, and postural tremor.

Blepharospasm-oromandibular dystonia, also called Meige dystonia or Meige syndrome is a focal dystonia (see this term) involving symmetrical benign essential blepharospasm (BEB) and oromandibular dystonia (see these terms).
